SCL, again, skin conductance level.

250
00:10:32,344 --> 00:10:34,306
This is measuring the electrical resistance of the skin.

251
00:10:34,546 --> 00:10:36,187
Basically, it could be you're sweating more,

252
00:10:36,207 --> 00:10:38,209
but it's actually the pH content of your sweat changes.

253
00:10:38,809 --> 00:10:40,190
You can conduct more current through your skin.

254
00:10:40,751 --> 00:10:43,453
And what you get is, essentially,

255
00:10:43,513 --> 00:10:45,034
the more current you can conduct

256
00:10:45,094 --> 00:10:46,395
is very highly correlated with arousal.

257
00:10:46,756 --> 00:10:48,637
So you get a waveform of arousal over time,

258
00:10:48,657 --> 00:10:49,518
which is actually pretty useful.

259
00:10:49,978 --> 00:10:52,179
And probably the coolest aspect of SEL

260
00:10:52,540 --> 00:10:55,461
is that you get spikes that usually have a lag time

261
00:10:55,501 --> 00:10:57,482
about one to three seconds, maybe two to five seconds,

262
00:10:57,502 --> 00:10:58,462
depending on who you talk to,

263
00:10:59,202 --> 00:11:00,783
in response to eliciting events.

264
00:11:01,363 --> 00:11:03,524
So if someone is having a SEL measure,

265
00:11:03,564 --> 00:11:05,005
I come up behind them and startle them,

266
00:11:05,025 --> 00:11:07,346
you'll see a spike, like an arousal,

267
00:11:07,366 --> 00:11:08,886
like one or two seconds later in the waveform,

268
00:11:08,986 --> 00:11:09,707
which is pretty cool.

269
00:11:10,107 --> 00:11:13,108
So you get almost instantaneous responses.

270
00:11:14,589 --> 00:11:17,170
Pros and cons of SEL, so it's a great index of arousal.

271
00:11:17,977 --> 00:11:18,917
Tonic and phasic responses.

272
00:11:18,937 --> 00:11:20,937
So tonic just refers to the overall level of arousal

273
00:11:20,957 --> 00:11:21,397
over time.

274
00:11:21,417 --> 00:11:24,858
So like heartbeat, you can tell generally

275
00:11:24,878 --> 00:11:27,078
where folks are being highly aroused or not.

276
00:11:27,438 --> 00:11:29,319
And you get the phasic responses, which are the spikes.

277
00:11:29,939 --> 00:11:32,919
So these just kind of transient little blips in arousal

278
00:11:32,959 --> 00:11:35,580
that we could actually do cool things with in gameplay.

279
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:38,521
So again, minimal lag to stimuli, very cheap,

280
00:11:39,201 --> 00:11:40,121
very robust to movement.

281
00:11:41,161 --> 00:11:43,562
We actually have a mouse that you can.

282
00:11:44,591 --> 00:11:46,192
The sensors are located on the palm,

283
00:11:46,232 --> 00:11:47,272
and it works pretty well.

284
00:11:47,312 --> 00:11:47,852
People can move around.

285
00:11:47,872 --> 00:11:48,372
It's not a problem.

286
00:11:48,392 --> 00:11:49,953
And you can measure in a lot of different places.

287
00:11:50,733 --> 00:11:52,914
We're focusing on easy-to-use devices that

288
00:11:52,934 --> 00:11:54,035
are kind of tied to the hands.

289
00:11:54,095 --> 00:11:56,395
But you could measure up by the mastoid process.

290
00:11:56,415 --> 00:11:57,776
You could actually do heartbeat here, actually,

291
00:11:57,836 --> 00:12:00,377
if you had a headset and had a clip here.

292
00:12:01,277 --> 00:12:04,619
But yeah, it's pretty robust and pretty intuitive, I guess,

293
00:12:04,639 --> 00:12:06,559
or at least pretty easy to use.

294
00:12:07,080 --> 00:12:09,380
One problem, although, again, you can get the spikes.

295
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:11,301
Because it is a waveform, or because it can be noisy,

296
00:12:11,321 --> 00:12:12,422
it can be difficult sometimes.

297
00:12:12,828 --> 00:12:13,809
to associated listening events,

298
00:12:13,849 --> 00:12:15,650
especially if you have multiple events in combination.

299
00:12:15,670 --> 00:12:16,710
If you're playing an action game,

300
00:12:17,111 --> 00:12:18,731
it can be difficult to determine which event

301
00:12:19,032 --> 00:12:20,772
actually caused the spike if a lot is going on.

302
00:12:21,433 --> 00:12:22,994
Again, difficult to determine valence,

303
00:12:23,014 --> 00:12:24,874
you know, it requires interpretation,

304
00:12:25,835 --> 00:12:28,376
which is not something that we want to do necessarily,

305
00:12:28,436 --> 00:12:31,258
but it's something that we kind of have to

306
00:12:31,298 --> 00:12:33,239
because we don't really get valence, we only get arousal.

307
00:12:33,679 --> 00:12:37,061
And one other interesting, I guess, concern with SEL

308
00:12:37,381 --> 00:12:38,821
is the range is variable across subjects.

309
00:12:39,162 --> 00:12:40,222
So you can get people who go from,

310
00:12:40,723 --> 00:12:43,065
you know, essentially it's one microsiemens to like two,

311
00:12:43,085 --> 00:12:44,946
you know, they could be really highly arousal

312
00:12:45,006 --> 00:12:46,668
and someone else could go from like two microsiemens

313
00:12:46,688 --> 00:12:47,388
at baseline to like 15.

314
00:12:48,309 --> 00:12:49,270
And so is that the same thing?

315
00:12:49,330 --> 00:12:50,891
Like, you know, is that two to 15 range

316
00:12:51,211 --> 00:12:52,512
equivalent to a one to two range?

317
00:12:52,532 --> 00:12:54,374
And how do you map, you know,

318
00:12:54,554 --> 00:12:55,635
the subjective feeling of arousal

319
00:12:55,655 --> 00:12:57,316
that someone is feeling to those ranges?

320
00:12:57,477 --> 00:12:58,277
So it's something to think about

321
00:12:58,317 --> 00:12:59,278
is that the range is a lot variable,

322
00:12:59,298 --> 00:13:00,059
whereas, you know, in heartbeat,

323
00:13:00,079 --> 00:13:01,800
you know, people, typical resting heartbeats,

324
00:13:01,820 --> 00:13:03,842
you know, fall in, you know, the 50 to 80 range.

325
00:13:03,942 --> 00:13:05,103
And, you know, you can kind of compute

326
00:13:05,443 --> 00:13:06,624
maximum heartbeat based upon.

327
00:13:07,209 --> 00:13:08,790
you know, age and gender and so forth.

328
00:13:08,890 --> 00:13:10,731
But with SEL, it's a little bit trickier.

329
00:13:14,073 --> 00:13:15,294
So facial expressions,

330
00:13:16,174 --> 00:13:18,276
this is just recording movement of the facial expressions,

331
00:13:18,516 --> 00:13:19,476
or sorry, facial muscles.

332
00:13:20,817 --> 00:13:22,518
It's really good at classifying emotion.

333
00:13:22,798 --> 00:13:24,939
You can get both balance and arousal pretty well

334
00:13:26,460 --> 00:13:27,421
by recording someone's face.

335
00:13:28,361 --> 00:13:29,702
You can do this remotely with cameras

336
00:13:29,742 --> 00:13:31,523
and have people code after the fact.

337
00:13:31,883 --> 00:13:33,064
There are companies that are starting

338
00:13:33,124 --> 00:13:35,606
to try and automate this process, which would be amazing.

339
00:13:35,626 --> 00:13:36,246
I don't know.

340
00:13:37,194 --> 00:13:39,155
I don't want to evaluate them here in this talk,

341
00:13:39,175 --> 00:13:40,596
but it's something that people are thinking about.

342
00:13:41,336 --> 00:13:43,758
You can also do it intrusively via EMG, which

343
00:13:43,838 --> 00:13:44,918
is electromyography.

344
00:13:44,958 --> 00:13:46,880
Essentially, it's just putting sensors

345
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,380
on various facial muscles, and you

346
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:49,461
can measure how much they contract.

347
00:13:49,521 --> 00:13:52,343
And you get really good measurements

348
00:13:52,403 --> 00:13:54,604
of what someone is feeling at any given point in time.

349
00:13:56,325 --> 00:13:58,827
So again, the work on facial expressions

350
00:13:58,847 --> 00:14:01,028
has been around for a really long time.

351
00:14:01,048 --> 00:14:02,349
It's well established.

352
00:14:02,529 --> 00:14:04,390
So here, this is the example of six.

353
00:14:07,517 --> 00:14:13,180
I guess, canonical human emotions, anger, surprise, disgust, sadness, happiness, and fear.

354
00:14:13,240 --> 00:14:15,401
And so you can detect all of these pretty readily.

355
00:14:15,421 --> 00:14:19,163
And you can detect the magnitude of these pretty readily by recording facial expressions.

356
00:14:20,944 --> 00:14:24,746
So the pros and cons, you know, it's great index surveillance, great index arousal.

357
00:14:24,766 --> 00:14:27,628
So you get the full picture of emotion and you get this instantaneously.

358
00:14:27,648 --> 00:14:30,809
You know, people, you know, your faces will respond involuntarily.

359
00:14:30,849 --> 00:14:33,811
I'm really bad at it. I can't hide my emotions even as much as I try.

360
00:14:33,851 --> 00:14:34,732
And so I will respond.

361
00:14:35,243 --> 00:14:37,444
really quickly and it can be frustrating,

362
00:14:37,484 --> 00:14:40,485
but again, at least in terms of its potential applicability

363
00:14:40,545 --> 00:14:43,546
to as an input to gameplay,

364
00:14:43,587 --> 00:14:45,447
having this instantaneous response is pretty cool.

365
00:14:46,088 --> 00:14:48,709
People will respond almost automatically to various things.

366
00:14:50,089 --> 00:14:52,650
The downsides, definitely intrusive,

367
00:14:52,751 --> 00:14:54,471
if people don't like having a camera on them

368
00:14:54,571 --> 00:14:56,072
or if you actually have the sensors on you,

369
00:14:56,112 --> 00:14:57,293
it's crazy intrusive.

370
00:14:57,893 --> 00:14:58,793
It's expensive at the moment,

371
00:14:59,513 --> 00:15:00,974
both in terms of time and money.

372
00:15:01,114 --> 00:15:03,635
Again, people are working on bringing this down to.

373
00:15:04,850 --> 00:15:07,551
automation through webcam, but we're kind of not there yet.

374
00:15:07,591 --> 00:15:09,371
And processing requires a lot.

375
00:15:09,391 --> 00:15:11,052
If you have a human coder who's watching people

376
00:15:11,112 --> 00:15:12,852
and categorizing, that can take a while.

377
00:15:13,432 --> 00:15:15,912
And if it is a human coder, they can be subject to bias.

378
00:15:16,133 --> 00:15:17,593
And then they also require training.

379
00:15:17,673 --> 00:15:21,354
But if you're depending on some kind of automated system,

380
00:15:21,634 --> 00:15:22,754
it's a black box, right?

381
00:15:22,774 --> 00:15:25,514
We'd like to kind of validate these techniques ourselves.

382
00:15:25,714 --> 00:15:27,395
SCL and Heartbeat, it's a lot easier to do that

383
00:15:27,795 --> 00:15:32,436
with software that's evaluating folks out of our hands.

384
00:15:32,476 --> 00:15:33,376
We don't like that, actually.

385
00:15:33,416 --> 00:15:34,216
That's kind of a

386
00:15:34,744 --> 00:15:36,486
a personal preference, but we want to kind of validate

387
00:15:36,506 --> 00:15:38,728
these things in-house, and so you do have to kind of depend

388
00:15:38,808 --> 00:15:41,690
on external algorithms to make determinations.

389
00:15:41,750 --> 00:15:43,932
And so it's up to you as to kind of how valid

390
00:15:43,952 --> 00:15:44,593
that ends up being.

391
00:15:44,753 --> 00:15:46,634
But I mean, just in terms of the potential applicability,

392
00:15:46,694 --> 00:15:48,476
facial expressions have a lot of promise.

393
00:15:51,198 --> 00:15:53,020
Fourth one is, so eye movements.

394
00:15:53,780 --> 00:15:55,502
Basically, we're just tracking where people are looking

395
00:15:55,562 --> 00:15:56,102
in real time.

396
00:15:56,923 --> 00:15:59,545
So you can use remote or head-mounted cameras

397
00:15:59,585 --> 00:16:01,147
to measure the reflectivity off of people

398
00:16:01,167 --> 00:16:02,428
as you shine an infrared light off the people.

399
00:16:02,838 --> 00:16:05,279
bounces off, and you can kind of get an idea of where someone

400
00:16:05,339 --> 00:16:05,819
is gazing.

401
00:16:07,240 --> 00:16:09,461
So you get a real-time record of where people are looking.

402
00:16:09,922 --> 00:16:12,043
And we require both eye movements and fixations.

403
00:16:12,103 --> 00:16:13,223
Eye movements are called saccades.

404
00:16:13,824 --> 00:16:15,405
Fixations, when the eye is stopped moving,

405
00:16:15,465 --> 00:16:16,925
or its eye is always really moving,

406
00:16:16,965 --> 00:16:18,906
but when the eye kind of centers on something

407
00:16:19,647 --> 00:16:21,968
for a little while, that's kind of like an index of processing.

408
00:16:22,348 --> 00:16:26,711
And I guess it's just a fun fact.

409
00:16:26,751 --> 00:16:28,832
So when your eye is actually moving, when you're saccading,

410
00:16:29,492 --> 00:16:30,913
visual input to the brain is suppressed.

411
00:16:31,438 --> 00:16:33,559
And so since we're making eye movements for about 2 and 1

412
00:16:33,719 --> 00:16:36,361
hours per day, you're effectively blind about 2

413
00:16:36,521 --> 00:16:37,281
and 1 hours per day.

414
00:16:37,441 --> 00:16:38,142
And we don't realize it.

415
00:16:38,982 --> 00:16:41,524
Just kind of something to keep in mind.

416
00:16:41,644 --> 00:16:43,965
So if you think about display is where you update the display

417
00:16:44,306 --> 00:16:45,967
when the eyes are moving, you could do whatever you wanted.

418
00:16:46,007 --> 00:16:48,628
And people wouldn't detect it until they stop moving.

419
00:16:48,668 --> 00:16:50,529
And so it's just there's a lot of potential use there,

420
00:16:50,549 --> 00:16:53,251
at least in terms of introducing surprising elements

421
00:16:53,291 --> 00:16:54,532
into the display when eyes are moving.

422
00:16:54,852 --> 00:16:55,692
We're a ways away from that.

423
00:16:55,812 --> 00:16:57,413
But again, trying to think about what

424
00:16:57,433 --> 00:16:58,514
could be possible in the future.

