00:17:59,764 --> 00:18:00,724
You can actually quantify these

452
00:18:00,764 --> 00:18:01,685
based on the trajectory.

453
00:18:02,319 --> 00:18:04,200
of the eye movements and the length of,

454
00:18:04,300 --> 00:18:05,641
I guess the length and number of fixations.

455
00:18:05,681 --> 00:18:08,763
And so, we'd like to think about that in the future

456
00:18:08,783 --> 00:18:10,524
in terms of like when we're play testing our games.

457
00:18:10,584 --> 00:18:11,484
Is that okay, we're like, you know,

458
00:18:11,644 --> 00:18:13,165
we can tell what people are doing

459
00:18:13,205 --> 00:18:13,925
at any given point in time.

460
00:18:13,965 --> 00:18:15,746
And so you get rudimentary insight into cognition

461
00:18:15,826 --> 00:18:17,787
just from where people's attention is landing,

462
00:18:17,988 --> 00:18:19,008
or at least where they're looking,

463
00:18:19,708 --> 00:18:20,809
which we think is pretty powerful.

464
00:18:22,590 --> 00:18:24,291
So pros and cons of eye movements.

465
00:18:24,551 --> 00:18:25,532
It's an index of attention, right?

466
00:18:25,552 --> 00:18:27,953
So it's not, you know, as tied to emotion

467
00:18:27,973 --> 00:18:28,533
as some of the other.

468
00:18:29,900 --> 00:18:31,842
I guess some of the other physiological signals,

469
00:18:31,922 --> 00:18:33,883
but again, you know, it's still pretty useful.

470
00:18:33,984 --> 00:18:36,145
And as I mentioned, it could be a rudimentary index

471
00:18:36,646 --> 00:18:37,046
of thought.

472
00:18:37,386 --> 00:18:38,867
And if you couple this with pupil dilation,

473
00:18:39,508 --> 00:18:41,149
which is, you know, a great correlate of arousal,

474
00:18:41,189 --> 00:18:42,490
you can get arousal as well.

475
00:18:42,610 --> 00:18:44,232
And so pretty much any eye tracker you buy

476
00:18:44,272 --> 00:18:46,233
will be able to measure pupil dilation.

477
00:18:47,034 --> 00:18:49,996
A unique metric and very, very reliable eye tracking

478
00:18:50,016 --> 00:18:51,337
technique is kind of mature now.

479
00:18:51,357 --> 00:18:53,779
It's still very expensive, but the technology is mature.

480
00:18:53,839 --> 00:18:56,061
So you get pretty good and pretty robust measurements

481
00:18:56,081 --> 00:18:56,922
of visual attention.

482
00:18:57,871 --> 00:19:02,993
The cons, it's incredibly expensive, the most expensive, probably the most expensive of all the signals at the moment.

483
00:19:03,874 --> 00:19:06,875
You know, I'm talking in the tens of thousands of dollars for an eye tracker.

484
00:19:07,215 --> 00:19:11,797
There are companies that are trying to bring that down by an order of magnitude, you know, in the five grand range.

485
00:19:12,137 --> 00:19:16,439
And then there actually, I know there's an open source project where people are trying to do this with webcams.

486
00:19:16,979 --> 00:19:22,701
I don't think it's there yet, but again, it's nice that people are trying to kind of bring this technology down to, you know, consumer price points.

487
00:19:23,822 --> 00:19:24,782
So, just something to think about.

488
00:19:25,866 --> 00:19:29,409
Other cons, it definitely requires a lot of analysis, post-hoc analysis.

489
00:19:29,429 --> 00:19:34,412
You can automate stuff and you can write scripts, but if you want to tag various features in the display,

490
00:19:34,432 --> 00:19:39,595
it can require a lot of analysis to do at least the quantification of scan pattern that I was talking about.

491
00:19:39,615 --> 00:19:42,077
That requires a lot of work as well.

492
00:19:42,177 --> 00:19:44,478
So you can get great data out of it, but you have to work for it.

493
00:19:45,259 --> 00:19:48,821
And then just one fact to it is that it can be intrusive as well.

494
00:19:49,322 --> 00:19:50,082
They've done studies where...

495
00:19:50,657 --> 00:19:56,440
You tell people you're tracking their eyes, or you don't, and the people who know their eyes are being tracked, you know, have different eye movements.

496
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:59,042
Like, they're more deliberate in their eye movements.

497
00:19:59,382 --> 00:20:04,425
So again, as with any kind of measurement technique, you know, we're introducing bias into the equation, unfortunately.

498
00:20:04,685 --> 00:20:10,489
But, you know, the data for the most part is pretty clean, but I didn't want to let you guys think that it was completely bias-free.

